      <div class="container">
        <h2>Understanding Percentiles</h2>

        <div class="info-cards">
          <div class="info-card">
            <h3>What is a Percentile?</h3>
            <p>A percentile is a measure used in statistics indicating the value below which a given percentage of observations in a group of observations falls. For example, the 20th percentile is the value (or score) below which 20% of the observations may be found.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="info-card">
            <h3>Test Scores</h3>
            <p>If you score in the 85th percentile on a standardized test, it means you scored higher than 85% of all people who took the test. It does not mean you got 85% of the questions correct. It purely measures your rank against your peers.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="info-card">
            <h3>Height and Weight</h3>
            <p>Pediatricians commonly use percentiles to track a child's growth. If a baby is in the 75th percentile for weight, they weigh more than 75% of babies their age, and less than 25%. This helps ensure they are growing at a healthy rate relative to typical population distributions.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="info-card">
