<section class="deep-dive-section" style="padding: 4rem 0; background-color: var(--card-bg); border-top: 1px solid var(--border-color);">
  <div class="container">
    <h2>The Mathematics of Percentiles</h2>
    <div style="column-count: 1; column-gap: 2rem;">
      <h3>Linear Interpolation in Percentiles</h3>
      <p>When calculating percentiles for a dataset, there are several distinct methods used by statisticians, software programs like Excel, and academic researchers. The method implemented in this calculator utilizes linear interpolation between closest ranks, which is identical to Excel's <code>PERCENTILE.INC</code> function. This ensures that the 0th percentile is exactly the minimum value of the dataset, and the 100th percentile is exactly the maximum value.</p>

      <h3>Formula for Percentile Rank</h3>
      <p>The percentile rank formula determines the relative standing of a specific value within a dataset. Let <em>x</em> be the target value. Let <em>c</em> be the count of values strictly less than <em>x</em>, and <em>f</em> be the count of values exactly equal to <em>x</em>. Let <em>N</em> be the total number of observations. The percentile rank <em>PR</em> is calculated as:</p>

      <div style="background: var(--bg-primary); padding: 1rem; border-radius: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); text-align: center; margin: 1rem 0; font-family: monospace; font-size: 1.1rem;">
        PR = [ (c + 0.5f) / N ] × 100
      </div>

      <p>This formula ensures that when there are multiple identical values in the dataset, the rank correctly reflects the middle position of that cluster of identical values, rather than pushing the rank artificially high or low.</p>

      <h3>Formula for Value at Percentile</h3>
      <p>To find the value corresponding to a specific percentile <em>P</em> (where 0 ≤ <em>P</em> ≤ 100), we first compute an index <em>i</em> based on the sorted dataset (indexed from 0 to N-1). We calculate:</p>

      <div style="background: var(--bg-primary); padding: 1rem; border-radius: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); text-align: center; margin: 1rem 0; font-family: monospace; font-size: 1.1rem;">
        i = (P / 100) × (N - 1)
      </div>

      <p>If <em>i</em> is an integer, the corresponding value in the sorted array is the exact answer. However, if <em>i</em> has a fractional component (e.g., 2.75), we must interpolate between the value at the integer floor (index 2) and the integer ceiling (index 3). We use the fractional part as a weight:</p>

      <div style="background: var(--bg-primary); padding: 1rem; border-radius: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); text-align: center; margin: 1rem 0; font-family: monospace; font-size: 1.1rem;">
        Value = V<sub>floor(i)</sub> + (i - floor(i)) × (V<sub>ceil(i)</sub> - V<sub>floor(i)</sub>)
      </div>

      <h3>Why Percentiles Matter More Than Averages</h3>
      <p>In data analysis, particularly when dealing with income, housing prices, or performance metrics, averages (means) can be highly misleading due to outliers. A single billionaire in a room of ten average earners will skew the mean income drastically higher, making it unrepresentative of the typical person in the room. This is why percentiles, and specifically the 50th percentile (the median), are crucial. The median provides a much more robust measure of central tendency because it is immune to extreme outliers.</p>
      <p>Furthermore, tail percentiles (like the 90th or 99th percentile) are essential for understanding risk and edge cases. In engineering, systems are rarely designed for the "average" load; they are designed for the 95th or 99th percentile load to ensure stability under stress.</p>

      <h3>Quartiles vs. Deciles vs. Percentiles</h3>
      <p>While percentiles divide data into 100 equal parts, there are other common quantiles used in statistics:</p>
      <ul style="padding-left: 2rem; margin-bottom: 2rem;">
        <li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;"><strong>Quartiles:</strong> Divide data into 4 parts (Q1 = 25th, Q2 = 50th, Q3 = 75th).</li>
        <li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;"><strong>Deciles:</strong> Divide data into 10 parts (D1 = 10th, D2 = 20th... D9 = 90th).</li>
        <li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;"><strong>Quintiles:</strong> Divide data into 5 parts (20th, 40th, 60th, 80th). Common in socioeconomic studies.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>All of these are simply specific subsets of percentiles. Our calculator explicitly breaks out quartiles and key upper percentiles (90th, 99th) because they are the most frequently requested summary statistics in both academia and business analytics.</p>

    </div>
  </div>
</section>

